[2]
Date: 20 Dec 2005
From: Alfonso Rodriguez, M.D.<ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Pravda news, Russia [edited]
<http://english.pravda.ru/accidents/21/97/384/16652_Chechnya.html>

13 children have been hospitalized with food poisoning in Chechnya during
the latest 24 hours. 4 children were staying in severe condition, doctors
said. The latest incident in Chechnya followed the previous hospitalization
of another group of children.
All the patients, majority of them girls, have similar symptoms: fatigue,
asphyxia and headache.
Specialists have not yet identified the type of poison, which affected the
schoolchildren. "A toxicological examination of the patients is required to
diagnose the disease," a Chechen doctor said.
Massive outbreaks of similar diseases have been registered in the same
region of the Chechen Republic 3 times during the past autumn. The symptoms
in all of the 3 incidents were identical, local doctors said.
13 schoolchildren and 2 teachers have been hospitalized in Chechnya's
Grozny since 16 Dec 2005.
Most patients were discharged by Monday, but they were replaced with
another group of sick schoolchildren the same day, Interfax reports.
Specialists say that the reason was not food, which did produce a massive
outbreak of poisoning in Chechnya. None of the hospitalized children has
eaten at the school canteen. In addition, the patients' symptoms show that
the poisoning was caused by toxic substances with neuroparalytic or
psychotropic action.
[Byline: Dmitry Sudakov]
